The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 Singapore, Oct. 30: Alcoa Inc is in talks to start producing 

aluminium in India despite facing severe problems with infrastructure in the country. 

Alcoa, which has no unit in India, wants to start supplying to one of the fastest-growing 

emerging markets and is considering a range of options that could include a joint 

venture or setting up its own production facilities.

 New Delhi, Oct. 30: Finance minister P. Chidambram will 

be working with a new team of bureaucrats with economic affairs secretary Ashok 

Jha appointed as the new finance secretary.

 New Delhi, Oct. 30: As the process to merge Air-India and 

Indian Airlines gathers momentum, a business model that is understood to have 

found acceptance among officials has recommended creating the post of a group 

CMD for the merged entity with special business units (SBUs) headed by separate 

CEOs.

 New Delhi, Oct. 30: Ashok Leyland has decided to set up 

a plant in Uttaranchal and will invest around Rs 1,100 crore in the new facility. 

According to sources, the company will set up base at a 175-acre plant in the 

Pantnagar area of the state, which offers excise and income tax breaks to investors.

 Mumbai, Oct. 30: Graphite India will split its equity shares 

in the ratio of 1:5. The board has approved the stock split, under which each 

equity share of Rs 10 would be split into five equity shares of Rs 2 each.

 Wuxi (China), Oct. 30: Larsen amp; Toubro today opened 

its first-ever electrical manufacturing facility abroad in the Chinese city of 

Wuxi. The company also announced plans to establish two more ventures in China 

 one in the valves sector and another in rubber. 

 London, Oct. 30: Shareholders have approved a new board 

for Mittal Steel Company. Aditya Mittal, Rene Lopez, Muni Krishna T. Reddy and 

ambassador Andres Rosental resigned as members of the board. 




